Five Year Accident History;

The Arclin, Springfield site, has had no accidental releases of ammonia or formaldehyde in the last five years that have caused any deaths, injuries, or significant property damage at the facility nor have there been any accidents which led to off-site deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property or environmental damage.



Emergency Response Program;

Arclin has established a facility emergency response plan that meets the requirements of both the OSHA PSM program and the EPA RMP program.  This response plan describes the procedures for coordinating with local emergency response agencies, provides documentation of proper first-aid and emergency medical treatment for accidental exposures, and outlines procedures for emergency response after a release.  Local emergency response and medical treatment personnel have worked with Arclin to provide for the safe control and treatment of releases of formaldehyde and ammonia.  Arclin employees receive training on emergency response procedures and emergency response equipment use.  Emergency response procedures are reviewed periodically and are reevaluated as part of the management of change and pre-startup review requirements of the PSM and RMP programs.



Planned Changes to Improve Safety;

Plant safety performance and capability relative to approved procedures, standards and practices is reviewed on an ongoing basis and is a primary factor considered in design and installation of all new and improved process equipment. The Arclin Spr

ingfield site has and continues to invest in improved technology and process control systems to provide enhanced process safety and production unit performance. 



Summary of Changes;

There has been no significant plant changes over the past 5-years that would modify the worst case or alternate case release scenarios.  No changes have been made that increases production capacity or operating temperatures or pressures that could reduce equipment reliability.
